metadata.value: [Peggy A. Rowe et al. case testimonies]: Department of the Interior, Commission to the Five Civilized Tribes, Chelsea, I. T., June 10, 1901 [3 copies]

metadata.label: abstract
metadata.value: Testimony of "Peggie Archer Rowe" and Katie Vann, for the enrollment of Peggie, her four children (Dinah, Katie, Annie, Ruthie) and three grandchildren (Clarence Simmons, Rogers Wheat, and Agnes Porter) as Cherokee Freedmen. Rowe testifies that she was born in Saline District in the Cherokee Nation, and that she and her sister, "Clarinda Vann," were sent by Polly Archer, their Cherokee enslaver, to Texas prior to the Civil War. Peggie testifies that although she returned to the Cherokee  Nation in 1866, she has resided in the Muscogee (Creek) Nation  with her husband, a Seminole Nation member named "George Rowe," ever since. Katie Vann testifies that she had seen Peggie in 1866 during a trip to Fort Gibson in the Cherokee Nation. Finally, Peggie is questioned about her oldest child "Cullie," who was born in the "Concharta District" [possibly "Concharty"?) in the Creek Nation. It is decided that Peggie and her family should be put on a "doubtful card" for further consideration, and that "satisfactory proof" is needed of the birth of her children and grandchildren, as they do not appear on any Cherokee tribal rolls.
